.\" %W% %G%
.TH Dgrid 2D D-language
.SH NAME
Dgrid \- Tool for overlaying a grid on a map
.br
.I (D Language Tool)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B Dgrid
[\fIsize\fR [\fIcolor\fR]]
.br
.B Dgrid
[option\*=\fIvalue\fR] [option\*=\fIvalue\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Dgrid 
draws a grid in the current graphics window.  The user can specify
grid size and color, either explicitly or positionally (see
.I DINTRO).
If grid size and color arguments are stated explicitly, their order
on the command line is immaterial.  The commands
.br
.IP
.B "Dgrid color\*=magenta size\*=1000"
.br
and
.br
.B "Dgrid size\*=1000 color\*=magenta"
.br
.LP
will therefore produce the same grid.  However, if arguments are stated
positionally, grid size must be stated before color (i.e.,
.B "Dgrid 1000 magenta").
If the user specifies only one option (either size or color), the
unspecified option becomes the default value.
.ns
.TP 
.RI size\*= size
Size of grid to be drawn.  If the user does not specify a grid size,
a 10,000 meter grid will be drawn by default in the current graphics
window.  It should be noted that, depending on the scale of the map layer
displayed in this window, this 10,000 meter grid may fall outside the
user's viewing range.
.br
.ns
.TP 
.RI color\*= color
Sets the current grid color.  Options are red, orange, green, blue,
yellow, indigo, violet, black, white, gray, brown, and magenta.  The
default color is white.
.LP
.I Dgrid
will not erase grids already created using
.I Dgrid;
multiple invocations of
.I Dgrid
will therefore result in the drawing of multiple grids inside the
current graphics window.
.SH "LIMITATIONS"
Currently, the grid size can only be drawn in the map's current coordinate
system.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.TS
ll.
\fIDINTRO[2D]\fR	Introduction to the GRASS \fID\fR tools
.TE
.SH "AUTHOR"
James Westervelt, U.S. Army Construction Engineering Research Laboratory
